When You Have “One Of Those Days”... 🤪😭

Reversing burnout is not a linear event…

It’s not like you wake up one day and you NEVER have to deal with fatigue, anxiety, or life stressors ever again…

This is important to remember when you feel like you have a breakthrough or several days or weeks where you feel like your burnout is completely in your past…

And then seemingly out-of-the-blue…

You feel like you are back at step one 😩😩😩

But this couldn’t be further from the truth…

Setbacks are a part of the process.

Having a setback doesn’t mean that you have done anything wrong or that your process or plan is not working...

It just means that you are having an off day 🤷🏼‍♀️

And one off day or off week does not need to turn into a permanent setback.

When I have an off day I do two things…

First, I offer myself grace and remind myself that perfectionism is not helpful in these situations.

Second, I step back and honestly evaluate the situation and any extenuating circumstances…

Have I been sticking to my foundational habits? Was there something that could have contributed to the setback? Where did I need to call in extra support or ask for help? 🤔

This helps me to take my eyes off the things I can’t control and put them back on the things that I can control…which helps me to reset and begin again.

If you are feeling like you are in the middle of a setback…reflect on your current situation, recenter yourself, and move forward with grace and ease. Doing so will help you return to balance more quickly 👏🏻👏🏻👏🏻

Gluten free vs consuming gluten? 🤷🏼‍♀️👇🏻

I often get asked what I believe about gluten-free vs not eliminating gluten in the diet so I thought I should take a minute and explain why I strongly stand behind and promote gluten-free over the latter 👏🏻😃

 At its core, food is either a gem or germ. It is either helping you or hurting you. In simplest terms, we eat to provide energy for growth, metabolism, and repair, and if that ‘energy’ came from an inflammatory  source, then the energy and downstream effects will be just that.

So how does gluten play into this? 
1️⃣ Gluten increases the production of a protein called “zonulin”. Zonulin, often referred to as the ‘seat of inflammation, is a small protein that wedges itself in between the tightly knit cells of the small intestine, creating a gap. (This is not good and is the basis of a leaky gut.)
2️⃣ Foreign substances and larger proteins that are not supposed to pass into the bloodstream are now allowed to do so. 
3️⃣ The bloodstream cannot handle these larger proteins so the immune system is called in to mount an attack against these ‘foreigners’, just as they would a bacteria or virus. 
4️⃣ As the immune system is distracted tending to the fire in the gut, it is unable to fight any real invaders. 
5️⃣ The immune system is now totally distracted and overwhelmed as chaos erupts and all body systems are susceptible to damage.

In my opinion, gluten is the single greatest source of inflammation found in food so that’s why I recommend eliminating it first! By making this one change you can greatly reduce the level of overall inflammation in your body as your gut starts to heal 😃👏🏻

The pros and cons of hormone replacement therapy 🤔🤷🏼‍♀️

One of the things that I often get asked about when it comes to relieving symptoms of night sweats, low energy, and vaginal dryness is bio-identical hormones (or HRT).

Bioidentical hormones have been used by providers for years to assist with symptoms related to menopause (or low sex hormones no matter the cause), but here are a few things that you should consider:

1️⃣ Bioidentical hormones need to be closely monitored and your hormone levels regularly tested. Ideally this is done through urine and insurance does not typically cover the costs. 

2️⃣ Bioidentical hormones may make you feel better as they replace hormone levels, however it is not getting to the root of WHY your levels are low. And if it's due to menopause, then you’re essentially fighting a natural process all women undergo. (There’s a reason why we stop producing as much estrogen + progesterone)

 3️⃣ Bioidentical hormones come with serious risks (hello, blood clots and breast cancer)

Let’s talk about burnout and sex drive (or lack thereof) 😳🫣😵

Yep...let’s do it…

It’s time to talk about low libido 💔

Nobody likes to talk about the fact that they have zero sex drive…

But when you are living with burnout it’s something we need to talk about…

It’s not TMI when you are living with it! 👏🏻

Let’s dive in, shall we? 👇🏻

The adrenal glands produce our primary stress hormone, cortisol. And after years of chronic stress, the adrenal glands start to get “tired” and cortisol levels drop. This leads to fatigue, increased infections, blood sugar imbalances, insomnia, brain fog, weight loss resistance, etc etc. The adrenal glands also produce our sex hormones: estrogen, progesterone, and testosterone. (Not to the degree the ovaries do in menstruating women, but the amount is still significant) So, as the adrenal glands start to tire and cortisol levels decline, so do our sex hormones. Which in turn relates to low sex drive, irregular cycles (or absence altogether, and infertility 😩😩

See, there IS a reason for your non-existent libido! 

My number one tip for improving low libido is to first start identifying the stressors in your life. Whether that’s your poor diet, lack of sleep, caffeine dependency, toxic relationships or work environment, etc and then one by one begin to address them.
